  "prompt": "What is a Shell in Unix OS?",
  "response": "In Unix and Unix-like operating systems, a shell is a command-line interface (CLI) that provides a way for users to interact with the operating system. Here are key details about shells:\n\n1. Basic Definition:\n- A shell is a program that interprets and executes user commands\n- It acts as an intermediary between the user and the operating system kernel\n- Provides a command-line interface for users to interact with computer systems\n\n2. Key Functions:\n- Command interpretation\n- Command execution\n- Input/output redirection\n- Pipeline creation\n- Environment variable management\n- Script execution\n- Process management\n\n3. Common Unix Shells:\n- Bash (Bourne Again Shell)\n- sh (Bourne Shell)\n- csh (C Shell)\n- ksh (Korn Shell)\n- zsh (Z Shell)\n\n4. Primary Types of Shells:\na. Command-line shells\nb. Graphical shells\nc. Script execution shells\n\n5. Shell Characteristics:\n- Provides prompt for user input\n- Supports command history\n- Offers programming constructs\n- Supports wildcard matching\n- Enables environment customization\n\n6. Basic Shell Operations:\n- Parsing commands\n- Expanding wildcards\n- Handling input/output\n- Managing processes\n- Executing system calls\n\nExample shell command:\n```bash\nls -l /home/user\n```",
